  "prompt": "Can someone build a product based on an idea he pitched to his ex company, if the company never cared to productize it?",
  "response": "Whether someone can build a product based on an idea pitched to a former company depends on several legal and ethical considerations:\n\n1. Employment Agreement\n- Check your previous employment contract\n- Look for clauses about intellectual property rights\n- Some contracts restrict developing ideas conceived during employment\n\n2. Non-Compete Agreement\n- Review any non-compete agreements you signed\n- Understand geographic and time restrictions\n- Ensure you're not violating any contractual terms\n\n3. Ownership of the Idea\n- Did the idea emerge entirely during your employment?\n- Were company resources used to develop the concept?\n- If the idea was fully developed by you, independently, you might have stronger grounds\n\n4. Patent and Confidentiality Considerations\n- Check if the company filed any patents related to the idea\n- Ensure you're not using confidential information\n\n5. Ethical Considerations\n- If the company explicitly showed no interest\n- If the idea was not pursued after reasonable opportunity\n- If you've made significant independent developments\n\nRecommended Steps:\n- Consult a legal professional\n- Review all previous agreements\n- Document your idea's independent development\n- Seek legal clearance before proceeding\n\nBest practice is to get professional legal advice tailored to your specific situation.",
